  <subsection xml:id="ssec-squeeze">
    <title>Limits by Squeezing</title>


<p>
  Some limits <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} f(x)</m> are difficult to evaluate because the function
  <m>f(x)</m> behaves erratically near <m>x=a</m>. For example:
</p>

<me>
  \lim_{x\to 1} \Bigl(x + 4(x-1)^2 \sin\!\bigl(\tfrac{1}{x-1}\bigr)\Bigr).
</me>

<p>
  The graph shows the unusual behavior, oscillating faster and faster near <m>x=1</m>
  because <m>\sin(\theta)</m> completes infinitely many periods as
  <m>\theta = \tfrac{1}{x-1}</m> becomes larger.
</p>



<sidebyside width = "90%">
<figure xml:id="fig-squeeze-oscillation">

  <caption>
     The function <m>y = x + 4(x-1)^2\sin\!\bigl(1/(x-1)\bigr)</m> (solid) squeezed between
    <m>y = x \pm 4(x-1)^2</m> (dashed).
  </caption>
  <image width = "100%" source="images/0102-g1.PNG">
  </image>
</figure>
</sidebyside>


<p>
  However, we can still find the limit using the <term>Squeeze Theorem</term>, which applies when
  <m>f(x)</m> is squeezed between two other functions. </p> 



    <theorem xml:id="thm-squeeze">
      <title>Squeeze Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>g(x) \leq f(x) \leq h(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> near <m>a</m> (except possibly <m>x=a</m>), and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} g(x) = \displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} h(x) = L</m>. Then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} f(x) = L</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
 

  <p> 
    Now let's apply the Squeeze Theorem to our example
  </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-squeeze-1">
      <title>Squeezing Example</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1} x + 4(x-1)^2\sin(\tfrac{1}{x-1})</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
<solution>
  <p>
    First note the expression is defined for <m>x \neq 1</m>, which is fine for a limit:
    we only need values of <m>x</m> near (but not equal to) <m>1</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Start from the basic bound true for every real <m>\theta</m>:
  </p>
  <me>
    -1 \;\le\; \sin(\theta) \;\le\; 1.
  </me>

  <p>
    Substitute <m>\theta = \tfrac{1}{x-1}</m> (valid when <m>x \neq 1</m>):
  </p>
  <me>
    -1 \;\le\; \sin\!\Bigl(\tfrac{1}{x-1}\Bigr) \;\le\; 1.
  </me>

  <p>
    Multiply the entire inequality by <m>4(x-1)^2</m>. Because
    <m>4(x-1)^2 \ge 0</m> for all <m>x</m>, the direction of the inequalities
    is preserved (multiplying by a nonnegative number does not flip signs):
  </p>
  <me>
    -\,4(x-1)^2 \;\le\; 4(x-1)^2 \sin\!\Bigl(\tfrac{1}{x-1}\Bigr) \;\le\; 4(x-1)^2.
  </me>

  <p>
    Now add <m>x</m> to each part of the inequality. Adding the same quantity to
    all three parts preserves the inequalities:
  </p>
  <me>
    x - 4(x-1)^2 \;\le\; x + 4(x-1)^2 \sin\!\Bigl(\tfrac{1}{x-1}\Bigr) \;\le\; x + 4(x-1)^2.
  </me>

  <p>
    Define the “floor” and “ceiling” functions
    <m>g(x)=x-4(x-1)^2</m> and <m>h(x)=x+4(x-1)^2</m>. Compute their limits
    using substitution:
  </p>
  <me>
    \lim_{x\to 1} g(x)
    \;=\; \lim_{x\to 1}\!\Bigl(x - 4(x-1)^2\Bigr)
    \;=\; 1
  </me>
  <me>
    \lim_{x\to 1} h(x)
    \;=\; \lim_{x\to 1}\!\Bigl(x + 4(x-1)^2\Bigr)
    \;=\; 1
  </me>

  <p>
    Since for all <m>x</m> near (but not equal to) <m>1</m> we have
    <m>g(x) \le x + 4(x-1)^2 \sin\!\bigl(\tfrac{1}{x-1}\bigr) \le h(x)</m>,
    and both bounding limits equal <m>1</m>, the Squeeze Theorem gives:
  </p>
  <me>
    \lim_{x\to 1} \Bigl(x + 4(x-1)^2 \sin\!\bigl(\tfrac{1}{x-1}\bigr)\Bigr) \;=\; 1.
  </me>

</solution>
    </example>

<remark>
  <p>
    Trigonometric functions are especially good candidates for the Squeeze Theorem, 
    since they have natural bounds. For example,
  </p>
  <me>
    -1 \leq \sin(\theta) \leq 1
  </me>
  <p>
    and
  </p>
  <me>
    -1 \leq \cos(\theta) \leq 1.
  </me>
  <p>
    These inequalities allow us to evaluate many limits involving 
    trigonometric functions by “squeezing” them between simpler functions.
  </p>
</remark>



    </subsection>

<exercises xml:id="tf-exercises-limits">
  <title>Practice / Study Problems</title>
  
  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Some True/False Problems</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Determine whether each statement is true or false and explain your reasoning
      </p>
    </introduction>

 <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} f(x) = 5</m> and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} g(x) = 7</m>, then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2}(f(x)+g(x))=12</m>.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>True.</alert> By the Sum Law: <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2}(f(x)+g(x))=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} f(x)+\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} g(x)=5+7=12</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 3} f(x) = 5</m>, then <m>f(3) = 5</m>.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>False.</alert> A limit concerns nearby values, not necessarily the value at the point. 
        For example, consider <xref ref="ex-canceling-zeros">Example</xref>. The limit exists even though the function itself is not defined 
        at the point.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\dfrac{x^2-1}{x-1} = 2</m>.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>True.</alert> Factor and cancel: <m>\dfrac{(x-1)(x+1)}{x-1}=x+1</m> for <m>x\neq 1</m>, so <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}(x+1)=2</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      The Limit Laws can always be applied, even if one of the limits does not exist.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>False.</alert> Each Limit Law requires the relevant limits to exist. If one does not exist, the law cannot be applied.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} f(x)=0</m> and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} g(x)=0</m>, then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2}\dfrac{f(x)}{g(x)}</m> must equal 1.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>False.</alert> The form <m>\tfrac{0}{0}</m> is meaningless. 
        For example, <m>f(x)=x-2</m>, <m>g(x)=2(x-2)</m> give <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2}\dfrac{f(x)}{g(x)}=\tfrac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      If <m>f(x)</m> is a polynomial, then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} f(x) = f(a)</m> for every real number <m>a</m>.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>True.</alert> Polynomials are continuous. We can apply the limit laws to substitute as discussed previously in this section. So <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} f(x)=f(a)</m> for all <m>a</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\dfrac{|x|}{x}</m> does not exist.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>True.</alert> <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0^-}\dfrac{|x|}{x}=-1</m> and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0^+}\dfrac{|x|}{x}=1</m>, so the two-sided limit does not exist.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\dfrac{x^2-4}{x-2} = -3</m>.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>False.</alert> Simplify to <m>x+2</m>, so <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}(x+2)=3</m>, not <m>-3</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0} x\sin(\tfrac{1}{x}) = 0</m>.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>True.</alert> By the Squeeze Theorem: <m>-|x|\leq x\sin(\tfrac{1}{x})\leq |x|</m>, and both bounds go to 0 as <m>x\to 0</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
      The Squeeze Theorem can be used to evaluate <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0} x^2\cos(\tfrac{1}{x})</m>.
    </p></statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>True.</alert> Since <m>-1\leq \cos(\tfrac{1}{x})\leq 1</m>, multiplying by <m>x^2\ge 0</m> gives <m>-x^2 \leq x^2\cos(\tfrac{1}{x}) \leq x^2</m>. Both bounds go to 0, so <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0} x^2\cos(\tfrac{1}{x})=0</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

</exercisegroup>

</exercises>

